# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: match-fixing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:match-fixing/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] The 1897–98 season was the tenth season of The Football League.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Beginning in the 1894–95 season, clubs finishing level on points were separated according to goal average (goals scored divided by goals conceded).
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] In case one or more teams had the same goal difference, this system favoured those teams who had scored fewer goals.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] The goal average system was eventually scrapped beginning with the 1976–77 season.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] During the first six seasons of the league, (up to the 1893–94 season), re-election process concerned the clubs which finished in the bottom four of the league.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] From the 1894–95 season and until the 1920–21 season the re-election process was required of the clubs which finished in the bottom three of the league.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Legend: Blue = home team win; Yellow = draw; Red = away team win.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Macdonald and Jane’s, London & Sydney, 1980.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] The Football League test matches were a set of play-offs, in which the bottom First Division teams faced the top Second Division teams.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Each First Division team plays both Second Division teams in a mini league format, the top two finishers would then be considered for election for First Division membership whilst the bottom two finishers would be invited to play in the Second Division.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] The First Division teams, if finishing in the top two, would retain their places in the division.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] If a Second Division team does so, it would be considered for First Division membership through an election process.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Bottom-two Second Division teams would stay in the Second Division.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Reference works, such *Encyclopedia of British Football*, and *Association Football* present the following table with the heading given above.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Burnley and Stoke City entered the last match needing a draw for promotion (or in Stoke's case to retain their First Division place).
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] A 0–0 draw ensued, reportedly 'The Match without a shot at goal' and the League immediately withdrew the Test Match system in favour of automatic promotion and relegation.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] Ironically, the League also decided to expand the top division to 18 teams after the Test Match series of 1897–98 and the other two teams, Blackburn Rovers and Newcastle United were elected into the top division for the following season, negating the effect of Burnley and Stoke's reputed collusion.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] In the end, the test matches and their results seem to have served no particular purpose.
[src:match-fixing/1897-98-football-league] After this season the test matches were scrapped in favour of direct promotion and relegation.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The **1899 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 through October 15, 1899, and saw the Brooklyn Superbas as the pennant winner of the National League.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 was the final season of a stable 12-team, eight-season run which saw no expansion or contraction of teams.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following the end of the season, the National League contracted from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league Western League to position themselves as a major league in 1901, by beginning a transition from a Midwest-focused league to the nationwide focused American League.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 season is famous for the Cleveland Spiders finishing with the worst single-season record of all time (minimum 120 games), finishing at a dismal 20–134 (.130), largely due to the fact that the Spiders-owning Robison family bought the St.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos prior to the 1899 season, then proceeded to move all Cleveland talent to St.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, leaving the Spiders a talent-depleted team.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The only other major-league team of the 19th century with a worse record was the 1884 Wilmington Quicksteps, who entered the unstable single-season Union Association as a late-season replacement for the Philadelphia Keystones and played only 18 games, with a record of 2–16 (.111).
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns renamed as the Brooklyn Superbas and St.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 schedule consisted of 154 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League in 1892 and the previous season.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final season which saw this format, due to the reduction of teams the following season.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 featuring four teams.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 15, featuring five teams play in four games (Chicago hosted Louisville and St.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis hosted Chicago, while Cincinnati hosted Cleveland in a doubleheader).
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] 20 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos, New Sportsman's Park, is renamed League Park.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The home of the Louisville Colonels, Eclipse Park, was destroyed in a fire on August 12, while the team was on a road trip.
[src:match-fixing/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following their return home, they would have a 12-game homestand from August 22 through September 2 in a partially rebuilt park, before spending the rest of the season on the road.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] The **1909 Scottish Cup final** was the final of the 36th season of the Scottish Cup.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] The match was an Old Firm affair contested by Rangers and Celtic at Hampden Park, with the trophy being withheld by the Scottish Football Association following crowd disorder.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] The final ended 2–2 on 10 April, prompting a replay which took place on 17 April.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] When that ended 1–1, the initial assumption was that extra time would follow, but competition rules only provided for that in the event of a second replay.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] When it became clear to the crowd that extra time would not be played, and fuelled by rumours that the results were manipulated to increase ticket revenue, the crowd invaded the pitch.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] In the ensuing disorder, the goalposts were torn down, parts of the pitch were ripped up and the wooden pay-boxes were set alight.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] Mounted police and the fire brigade also came under attack and in total there were over 100 injuries.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] Both clubs requested the SFA not schedule a second replay and subsequently, the trophy and medals were withheld.
[src:match-fixing/1909-scottish-cup-final] Queen's Park F.C., the owners of Hampden, were paid £500 in compensation by the SFA, who ordered both competing clubs to pay an additional £150 each.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1919 Chicago White Sox season** was their 19th season in the American League.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] They won 88 games to advance to the World Series but lost to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] More significantly, some of the players were found to have taken money from gamblers in return for throwing the series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The "Black Sox Scandal" had permanent ramifications for baseball, including the establishment of the office of Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] In 1919, Eddie Cicotte led the majors with 29 wins and 30 complete games, going 29–7 for the season with a 1.82 ERA (2nd in AL) and 110 strikeouts (7th in AL).
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] He also led the AL in innings pitched with 240 (shared with Washington Senators pitcher Jim Shaw).
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Right fielder Joe Jackson hit .351 (4th in AL) with 7 home runs, 96 RBIs (3rd in AL) and had 181 hits (3rd in AL, only 10 fewer than league leader Ty Cobb of the Detroit Tigers).
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Shoeless Joe headed an offense that scored the most runs of any team.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The **Black Sox Scandal** refers to a number of events that took place around and during the play of the 1919 World Series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The name "Black Sox" also refers to the Chicago White Sox team from that era.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Eight members of the Chicago franchise were banned from baseball for throwing (intentionally losing) games.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The conspiracy was the brainchild of White Sox first baseman Arnold "Chick" Gandil and Joseph "Sport" Sullivan, who was a professional gambler of Gandil's acquaintance.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] New York gangster Arnold Rothstein supplied the major connections needed.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] The money was supplied by Abe Attell, former featherweight boxing champion, who accepted the offer even though he didn't have the $80,000 that the White Sox wanted.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Gandil enlisted seven of his teammates, motivated by a mixture of greed and a dislike of penurious club owner Charles Comiskey, to implement the fix.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Starting pitchers Eddie Cicotte and Claude "Lefty" Williams, outfielders "Shoeless" Joe Jackson and Oscar "Happy" Felsch, and infielder Charles "Swede" Risberg were all involved.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Buck Weaver was also asked to participate, but refused; he was later banned with the others for knowing of the fix but not reporting it.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Utility infielder Fred McMullin was not initially approached but got word of the fix and threatened to report the others unless he was in on the payoff.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Sullivan and his two associates, Sleepy Bill Burns and Billy Maharg, somewhat out of their depth, approached Rothstein to provide the money for the players, who were promised a total of $100,000.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] Stories of the "Black Sox" scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid Cicotte an additional $10,000 bonus for winning 30 games.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win, presumably to deny him the bonus.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] In reality, however, Cicotte started the White Sox's last game of the season, September 28th against the Tigers.
[src:match-fixing/1919-chicago-white-sox-season] But, with a 1-0 Chicago lead, Chicago manager Kid Gleason took Cicotte out of the game following the second inning, which assured Cicotte could not get his 30th win.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The **1919 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the 1919 season.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The 16th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox against the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Although most World Series have been of the best-of-seven format, the 1919 World Series was a best-of-nine series (along with 1903, 1920, and 1921).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The National Baseball Commission decided to try the best-of-nine format partly to increase popularity of the sport and partly to generate more revenue.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The events of the 1919 World Series are often associated with the Black Sox Scandal, in which several members of the Chicago franchise conspired with gamblers, allegedly led by organized crime figure Arnold Rothstein, to throw the series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] This led the various franchise owners to install Kenesaw Mountain Landis as the first Commissioner of Baseball in 1920.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In August 1921, despite being acquitted from criminal charges, eight players from the White Sox were banned from organized baseball for either fixing the series or having knowledge about the fix without alerting the league.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, another player on the team who was not involved in the scandal, was later suspended after holding out for more pay, but was eventually reinstated.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] They were the first players formally banned in the modern era, and, as it turned out, the template for how Landis would wield his authority throughout his tenure.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] On May 12, 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred lifted all permanent bans — including those of the Black Sox players — on the grounds that deceased players pose no threat to the integrity of the game.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The nine players that were once banned by the MLB (most notably Shoeless Joe Jackson and Eddie Cicotte) are now considered eligible for entry into the Baseball Hall of Fame by as early as 2027.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In 1919, the Chicago White Sox, who had won the World Series two years earlier, had the best record in the American League (AL).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Most of the same players had defeated the New York Giants in the 1917 series, four games to two.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] They had fallen to sixth place in the American League in 1918, largely as a result of losing their best player, Shoeless Joe Jackson, and a few other teammates to World War I service.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The team's owner, Charles Comiskey, fired manager Pants Rowland after the season and replaced him with William "Kid" Gleason, who had played over twenty years in the majors but had never managed before.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The 88–52 White Sox won the American League pennant again in 1919, by 3+1⁄2 games over the Cleveland Indians (world champions the following year).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Jackson was the unquestioned star of the White Sox.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The left fielder hit .351 that season, fourth in the league and in the AL's top five in slugging percentage, RBI, total bases and base hits.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] He was not the only star in a lineup with hardly a weak spot, as former Philadelphia Athletics superstar leadoff hitter Eddie Collins, one of the greatest second basemen of all time, was still going strong in his early thirties, hitting .319 with a .400 on-base percentage.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Right fielder Nemo Leibold hit .302 with 81 runs scored.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] First baseman Chick Gandil hit .290, third baseman Buck Weaver .296, and center fielder Oscar "Hap" Felsch hit .275 and tied Jackson for the team lead in home runs with only seven (as the dead-ball era was coming to a close).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Even typical "good field, no hit" catcher Ray Schalk hit .282 that year, and shortstop Swede Risberg was not an automatic out with the .256 average and 38 RBI.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Gleason's bench contained two impressive hitters, outfielder Shano Collins and infielder Fred McMullin, both veterans of the 1917 series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Eddie Cicotte recorded a 29–7 record, leading the league in wins and ranking second in earned run average to Walter Johnson.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Claude "Lefty" Williams finished with a 23–11 record and a 2.64 ERA.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr started 17 games and recorded a 13–7 record with a 2.88 ERA.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Urban "Red" Faber had an 11–9 record with a 3.83 ERA in 20 starts.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Faber was unable to pitch in the series due to illness, leaving manager Kid Gleason with three starting pitchers.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] However, all was not well in the White Sox camp.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In contrast to the White Sox, the 1919 Cincinnati Reds were upstarts.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] They had finished no higher than third since 1900, and then only twice, before winning the National League (NL) pennant handily in 1919.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The Reds' greatest star was center fielder Edd Roush, who led the league in hitting at .321 and, like the White Sox's Jackson, was in the top five of their respective leagues in most important hitting categories.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Third baseman Heinie Groh was the other great hitter on the team at .310 with a .392 on-base percentage and 79 runs scored.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Slick-fielding first baseman Jake Daubert, a two-time National League batting champion with Brooklyn earlier in the decade, also scored 79 runs and hit .276, while catcher Ivey Wingo hit .273.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The rest of the team was unheralded, including second baseman Morrie Rath, a .264 hitter with no power but a good on-base percentage, and shortstop Larry Kopf, a .270 singles hitter.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The corner outfielders were decidedly weaker hitters, with former Phillies star left fielder Sherry Magee's .215 in 56 games and right fielder Earle "Greasy" Neale's .242 with little power.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] This would prompt Moran to start rookie Pat Duncan in left field in the 1919 series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] However, the Reds had a strong pitching rotation.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The team's big three included Hod Eller (20–9, 2.39), Dutch Ruether (19–6, 1.82) and Slim Sallee (21–7, 2.06), all among the league leaders in various categories.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] They were backed by three other pitchers who were almost as successful: Jimmy Ring at only 10–9 but 2.26, Ray Fisher at 14–5 and 2.17 with five shutouts, and Cuban Dolf Luque at 10–3 and 2.63, former and future Giant who would win the last game of the 1933 World Series in long relief for New York.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The conspiring players on the White Sox got an unexpected assist when a flu-stricken Faber was left off the World Series roster.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Indeed, years later, catcher Schalk said that had Faber been healthy, there never would have been a fix (since he almost certainly would have gotten starts that went to Cicotte or Williams).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Despite their many wins on the field, the Sox were an unhappy team.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Many observers blame their attitude on Comiskey's stinginess, despite the fact that the 1919 White Sox payroll was third highest in the AL, behind only Boston and New York.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Stories about the scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid the knuckleballer an additional $10,000 bonus for winning thirty games.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win presumably to deny him the bonus, but the truth may be more complex.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Cicotte won his 29th game on September 19, had an ineffective start on September 24 and was pulled after a few innings in a tuneup on the season's final day, September 28 (three days before the World Series opener).
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In addition, Cicotte reportedly agreed to the fix the same day he won his 29th game before he could have known of any efforts to deny him a chance to win his 30th.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The story was probably true with regard to the 1917 season, however, when Cicotte won 28 games and hurled the White Sox to the championship.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The first game began at 3 pm at Cincinnati's Redland Field, with 30,511 fans in the stands and ticket scalpers outside the park raking in at least $50 per ticket.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Chicago failed to score in the top of the first.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Cicotte (who was paid his $10,000 the night before the series began) took the mound and hit the leadoff hitter (and former teammate), Morrie Rath, in the back with his second pitch, a prearranged signal to Arnold Rothstein that the fix was on.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Even so, the game remained close for a while, due in part to some excellent defense from the conspirators, seeking to deflect suspicion from themselves.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In the fourth, however, Cicotte "went haywire" (again according to Meany, *op. cit.*), allowing a number of hits in succession climaxed by a two-out triple to the opposing pitcher, as the Reds scored five times to break a 1–1 tie.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Cicotte was relieved at that point, but the damage was done and the Reds went on to add three more runs in later innings and win 9–1.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Sportswriters thought that a bad throw by Cicotte to Risberg in the fourth inning, which prevented a possible double play, was suspicious.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] By that evening, there already were signs that things were going wrong.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Only Cicotte, who had shrewdly demanded his $10,000 in advance, had been paid.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] "Sleepy" Bill Burns and Maharg met with Abe Attell, the former world boxing champ and Rothstein's intermediary, but he withheld the next installment ($20,000) nonetheless to bet on the next game.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The next morning Gandil met Attell and again demanded money, but again to no avail.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Although they had not received their money, the players were still willing to go through with the fix.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] "Lefty" Williams, the starting pitcher in Game 2, was not going to be as obvious as Cicotte.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] After a shaky start, he pitched well until the fourth inning, when he walked three and gave up as many runs.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] After that he became virtually unhittable again, giving up only one more run; but lack of clutch hitting, with Gandil a particularly guilty party, led to a 4–2 White Sox loss.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Attell was still in no mood to pay up afterwards, but Burns managed to get hold of $10,000 and gave it to Gandil, who distributed it among the conspirators.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The teams headed northwest to Comiskey Park in Chicago for Game 3 the next day, with no days off for travel in this Series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Rookie pitcher Dickey Kerr, the Game 3 starter for the Sox, was not in on the fix.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The original plan was for the conspirators, who disliked Kerr, to lose this game, but by now dissent among the players meant that the plan was in disarray.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Burns still had faith and gathered the last of his resources to bet on Cincinnati.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] It was a decision that would leave him broke, as Chicago scored early—with Gandil himself driving in two runs—and Kerr was masterful, holding the Reds to three hits in a 3–0 complete game shutout.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Cicotte took the mound again for Game 4, and was determined not to look as bad as he had in Game 1.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] For the first four innings, he and Reds pitcher Jimmy Ring matched zeroes.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] With one out in the fifth, Cicotte fielded a slow roller by Pat Duncan but threw wildly to first for a two-base error.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The next man up, Larry Kopf, singled to left; Cicotte cut off the throw from Jackson and fumbled the ball, allowing Duncan to score.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The home crowd was stunned by the veteran pitcher's obvious mistake.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Cicotte then surrendered a double to Greasy Neale which scored Kopf to make it 2–0; this was enough of a lead for Ring, who hurled a three-hit shutout of his own, matching Kerr's in Game 3.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] After the game "Sport" Sullivan came through with $20,000 for the players, which Gandil split equally among Risberg, Felsch, and Williams, who was due to start Game 5 the next day.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Both starters, Williams and Cincinnati's Hod Eller, pitched excellently at first, with neither allowing a runner past first until the top of the sixth, when Eller himself hit a blooper that fell between Felsch and Jackson.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Felsch's throw was offline, sending Eller all the way to third.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Leadoff hitter Morrie Rath then singled over the drawn-in infield, scoring Eller.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Heinie Groh walked before Edd Roush's double—the result of more doubtful defense from Felsch—brought home two more runs, with Roush scoring shortly thereafter.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Eller pitched well enough (he struck out nine batters, including a then-World Series record six in a row, since tied by Moe Drabowsky in the 1966 World Series opener) for the four runs to stand up, and the Reds were only one game away from their first world championship.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The Series reverted to Cincinnati for Game 6.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, starting for the White Sox, was less dominant than in Game 3.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Aided by three White Sox errors, the Reds jumped out to a 4–0 lead before Chicago fought back, tying the game at 4–4 in the sixth, which remained the score into extra innings.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In the top of the tenth, Gandil drove in Weaver to make it 5–4, and Kerr closed it out to record his — and Chicago's — second win.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Despite the rumors already circulating about Cicotte's erratic performances in Games 1 and 4, White Sox manager Kid Gleason showed faith in his ace for Game 7.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] This time, the knuckleballer did not let him down.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Chicago scored early and, for once, it was Cincinnati that committed errors.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The Reds threatened only briefly in the sixth before losing 4–1, and suddenly the Series was relatively close again.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] This marked the only time in World Series history that the winner of Game 7 did not ultimately go on to win the series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] This did not go unnoticed by Sullivan and Rothstein, who were suddenly worried.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Before the Series started, the Sox had been strong favorites and few doubted they could win two games in a row—presuming that they were *trying* to win.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Rothstein had been too smart to bet on individual games, but had $270,000 riding on Cincinnati to win the Series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The night before Game 8, Williams—the scheduled starter—was supposedly visited by an associate of Sullivan's known as Harry F.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] He left no doubt that if Williams failed to blow the game in the first inning, he and his wife would be in serious danger.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Chicago wouldn't see another Game 7 for over a century.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Whatever Williams had been told made its impression.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] In the first, throwing nothing but mediocre fastballs, he gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before Gleason relieved him with "Big" Bill James, who allowed one of Williams' baserunners to score.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] James continued ineffective and, although the Sox rallied in the eighth, the Reds came away with a 10–5 victory for a five-games-to-three Series win.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Jackson hit the only homer of the Series in the third inning after the Reds had built a 5–0 lead.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Immediately after the Series ended, rumors were rife from coast to coast that the games had been thrown.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Journalist Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner*, disgusted by the display of ineptitude with which the White Sox had "thrown" the series, wrote that no World Series should ever be played again.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Jackson led all players with his .375 average.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Some believed that most of his offensive potency came in games that were not fixed and/or when the game seemed out of reach.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] He hit the Series' lone home run in the eighth and final game, a solo shot in the third inning, by which time the Reds were already ahead 5–0.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] His five hits with runners in scoring position came in: Game 6, sixth inning with Kerr pitching; Game 7, first and third innings; Game 8, two in the four-run eighth.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] Shoeless Joe had 12 hits overall, a World Series record at that time and tied for the most in an eight-game series.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The Reds would make their next World Series appearance two decades later, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the last victim of a Yankees dynasty of four straight championships from 1936 to 1939.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] They would win their next championship in 1940 over the Detroit Tigers in seven games after being nine outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:match-fixing/1919-world-series] The scandal cast a shadow that lasted decades.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The **1946 NFL Championship Game** was the 14th annual championship game of the National Football League (NFL), played December 15 at the Polo Grounds in New York City, with a record-breaking attendance of 58,346.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The game matched the New York Giants (7–3–1), champions of the Eastern Division, against the Western Division champion Chicago Bears (8–2–1).
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The Giants had won the regular season game 14–0 at the Polo Grounds seven weeks earlier on October 27, but the Bears were seven to ten point favorites.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] It was the fourth championship game in the history of the Bears-Giants rivalry.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] This was the fifth and final NFL Championship game played at the Polo Grounds and the fourth of six meetings between the Bears and Giants in the title game.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Tied after three quarters, Chicago won 24–14 for their seventh NFL title, their fifth victory in eight NFL championship game appearances.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The attendance record stood for another nine years, until the 1955 title game in Los Angeles.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The day before the game, two of the Giants' players, Frank Filchock and Merle Hapes, were accused of taking bribes to fix the game from Alvin Paris.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Mayor William O'Dwyer subsequently informed Jack Mara, Wellington Mara and Bert Bell of the police evidence against the two.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Hours later, the four met at Gracie Mansion, and the mayor interviewed the players one at a time.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Under questioning, Hapes admitted that he was offered a bribe, but Filchock denied being offered it.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Several hours later, Paris was arrested, and during his police interview made a full confession to bribing the players: Hapes was suspended by Bell, but Filchock was allowed to play.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] During Paris' trial weeks later, Filchock admitting taking the bribe under oath.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The NFL had only four game officials in 1946; the back judge was added the following season in 1947, the line judge in 1965, and the side judge in 1978.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] The gross receipts for the game, including radio and picture rights, was just under $283,000.
[src:match-fixing/1946-nfl-championship-game] Each player on the winning Bear team received $1,975, while Giants players made $1,295 each.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] There are many reasons why match fixing might take place, including receiving bribes from bookmakers or sports bettors, and blackmail.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Competitors may also intentionally perform poorly to gain a future advantage, such as a better draft pick or to face an easier opponent in a later round of competition.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A player might also play poorly to rig a handicap system.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Match fixing, when motivated by gambling, requires contacts (and normally money transfers) between gamblers, players, team officials, and/or referees.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] These contacts and transfers can sometimes be discovered, and lead to prosecution by the law or the sports league(s).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In contrast, losing for future advantage is internal to the team and very difficult to prove.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Match fixing includes point shaving and spot-fixing, which center on smaller events within a match that can be wagered upon but are unlikely to prove decisive in determining the game's final result.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] According to Sportradar, a company that monitors the integrity of sports events on behalf of sports federations, as many as one percent of the matches they monitor show suspicious betting patterns that may be indicative of match fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In sports where a handicap or ranking system exists and is capable of being abused (including sports such as racing, grappling and golf), throwing the game is known as "sandbagging".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Hustling, where a player disguises his abilities until he can play for large amounts of money, is a common practice in many cue sports, such as nine-ball pool.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Some major motivations behind match fixing are gambling and team advantages.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] According to investigative journalist Declan Hill it has also been linked to corruption, violence and tax avoidance.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In Eastern Europe, organized crime is linked to illegal gambling and score fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In Russia, people have disappeared or been murdered after acting against bribery in sports.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] There may be financial gain through agreements with gamblers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of 1919, in which several members of the MLB's Chicago White Sox conspired with gamblers to fix that year's World Series for monetary gain.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] One of the best-known examples of gambling-related race fixing (in motorsports) is the 1933 Tripoli Grand Prix, in which the winning number of the lottery was determined by the number of the race-winning car.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] One ticket holder held the number belonging to Achille Varzi, contacted him and agreed to share the winning should he win.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Varzi contacted other drivers who agreed to share the money if they deliberately lost.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Despite a poor start, Varzi won the race after his opponents deliberately underperformed throughout the race.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A large match-fixing ring in the lower levels of professional tennis, centered around gambling, was broken up in 2023.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A similar organized effort in Chinese and NCAA basketball was uncovered in 2026.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Match fixing can also occur when teams or athletes manipulate the outcome of a match to gain a strategic or competitive advantage rather than direct financial benefit.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In such cases, the aim may be to influence standings, improve seeding, or create conditions that benefit a particular competitor.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In sports such as Formula One, where each team fields two drivers, teams have at times used one driver to create a strategic advantage for the other.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] While team orders themselves are not inherently match fixing, controversies such as Crashgate demonstrate how the pursuit of competitive advantage can motivate deliberate manipulation of a sporting event.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In this case, Renault driver Nelson Piquet Jr. was instructed to crash deliberately, exploiting the safety car rule to benefit his teammate Fernando Alonso, enabling him to win the 2008 Singapore Grand Prix.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Many sports have tournaments where the result of one round determines their opponent in the next round.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As a result, by losing a match, a team can face an easier opponent in the next round, making them more likely to win.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the only one of the four major professional sports leagues of the United States and Canada in which home advantage in the playoffs is based strictly on regular-season records without regard to seeding.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The top six teams earn an automatic playoff berth, while the seventh through tenth teams compete for the last two seeds in a "play-in tournament".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As of the 2022 season, no Western team has advanced to the Grey Cup championship game from the Eastern bracket.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] An earlier example of possible match fixing occurred in the ice hockey competition at the 2006 Winter Olympics.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In Pool B, Sweden was to face Slovakia in the last pool match for both teams.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Sweden coach Bengt-Åke Gustafsson publicly contemplated losing against Slovakia, knowing that if his team won, their quarterfinal opponent would either be Canada, the 2002 gold medalists, or the Czech Republic, 1998 gold medalists.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Canada would lose to Russia in a quarterfinal in the opposite bracket, while Sweden went on to win the gold medal, defeating the Czechs in the semifinals.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The 1998 Tiger Cup – an international football tournament contested by countries in Southeast Asia – saw an example of two teams trying to lose a match.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The tournament was hosted by Vietnam, with the eight countries competing split into two groups of four.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The top two in each group advanced to the semi-finals with the winners playing the runners-up of the other group.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As the two teams involved – Thailand and Indonesia – had both already qualified for the semi-finals, it was in both teams' interest to lose the match and finish in second place.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As the game progressed, neither side seemed particularly concerned with scoring, while the defending was lackadaisical.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As the match entered stoppage time, Indonesian defender Mursyid Effendi scored an own goal, overcoming the efforts of several Thai players and the goalkeeper to stop him.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Both teams were fined $40,000, and Effendi was banned from international football for life.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In the final month of the 2010 Major League Baseball season, the New York Yankees and Tampa Bay Rays were in a tight race for the American League East division title and by the final week, both teams had already clinched at least the wild card.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Yankees went 3–7 over the final 10 games, losing their regular-season finale, while the Rays went 5–5 and won theirs, giving the Rays the AL East title by one game and the Yankees the AL wild-card berth.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Winning the division would have given New York an ALDS matchup against the Texas Rangers, who at the time had star pitcher Cliff Lee; the Yankees instead defeated the Minnesota Twins, a team they historically have had more postseason success against.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Allegations of the Yankees purposefully settling for the wild card, presumably to avoid facing Texas in the ALDS, began to surface after the Yankees defeated the Twins.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Additional allegations came up in 2012 when Yankees general manager Brian Cashman commented in response to a possible playoff expansion that his team had "conceded the division" and that winning it meant "nothing more than a T-shirt and a hat".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] However, Cashman insisted that the Yankees were not motivated by any desire to lose games, but were merely ensuring their best players were well-rested for the postseason, which he contended was perfectly ethical behavior.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In 2012, Major League Baseball added a second wild card in each league, with the two wild cards playing a single-elimination game in order to give more importance to winning the division.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In 2022, the postseason was further expanded, adding a third wild card and making the round a best-of-three series.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Match fixing can also happen in high-school level sports.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] For example, In February 2015, two girls' basketball teams representing Nashville-area Riverdale and Smyrna High Schools were both intentionally trying to lose during a consolation match of their district tournament.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The winner of the game would enter the same side of the regional tournament bracket as defending state champion Blackman High School (ranked as one of the country's top 10 teams by some national publications), setting up a potential match in the regional semifinals.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The loser would thus avoid Blackman until the regional final, a game whose participants would both advance to the sectional tournament (one step short of the state tournament).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] During the game both teams pulled their starters early, missed shots on purpose, intentionally turned over the ball and deliberately committed fouls.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association, which governs high school sports in the state, ejected both teams from the postseason, fined the two schools (Riverdale $1,000 and Smyrna $500), and placed both teams on probation through the 2015–16 school year.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] For example, during Euro 2004 the Czech Republic rested nearly all of its starters from the first two group matches for the final group match against Germany.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Since the Czechs had already clinched first place in the group, this move was seen to have the potential to allow Germany a better chance to get the win they needed to advance at the expense of the winner of the Netherlands–Latvia game.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As it happened, the Czechs' decision to field a "weaker" side did not matter since the Czechs won the match anyway to eliminate the Germans.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Most top-level sports leagues in North America and Australia hold drafts to allocate young players to the league's teams.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The order in which teams select players is often the inverse of their standings in the previous season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As a result, a team may have a significant incentive to tank games to secure a higher pick in the league's next draft, and a number of leagues have changed their draft rules to remove (or at least limit) potential incentives to tank.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] From 1966 to 1984, the NBA used a coin flip between the teams with the worst records in each of the league's two conferences to determine the recipient of the top pick.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In the 1983–84 season, several teams were accused of deliberately losing games in an attempt to gain a top position in the 1984 draft, which would eventually produce four Hall of Fame players.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As a result of this, the NBA established a draft lottery in advance of the 1985 draft, involving all teams that did not make the playoffs in the previous season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] This lottery system prevented teams from receiving fixed draft positions based on record place, which the league hoped would discourage them from deliberately losing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Even though the lottery in place through the 2018 draft gave the team with the worst record only the same chance at the top pick as the 2nd and 3rd worst teams (with that team guaranteed no worse than the fourth pick), there was still perceived incentive for a team to tank.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Responding to these perceived incentives, the NBA further tweaked its lottery rules shortly before the start of the 2017–18 season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Effective with the 2019 draft, the teams with the three worst records have equal odds of landing the #1 pick (barring one of these teams also owning another lottery team's pick), and the top four picks are allocated in the lottery instead of the top three.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] This limits but does not eliminate the incentive to tank, particularly when there is at least one exceptional prospect.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Australian Football League, the main competition of Australian rules football, has used a system of priority draft picks since 1993, with poorly performing teams receiving extra selections at or near the start of the draft.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Prior to 2012, a team automatically received a priority pick if its win–loss record met pre-defined eligibility criteria.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] However, that system led to accusations of tanking by several clubs—most notably by Melbourne in 2009 (the club was found not guilty, but the head coach and general manager were found guilty on related charges).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Since 2012, priority picks are awarded at the discretion of the AFL Commission, the governing body of both the AFL and the overall sport.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Until the 2014–15 NHL season, the National Hockey League assured the last place team of at least the second position in its entry draft, with the first overall pick being subject to a draft lottery among the five worst teams.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] However, in 2014–15, two elite prospects widely considered to be "generational talents", Connor McDavid and Jack Eichel, were projected to enter the 2015 NHL entry draft, thus ensuring the last place team at least one of the two prospects.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] This was most prominent with the Buffalo Sabres, whose fans openly rooted against their team in the hopes they would clinch last place in the league for much of the season (the Sabres themselves denied they were tanking and openly criticized their fans for suggesting the notion).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Beginning in 2015–16, the top three picks in the draft are subject to lottery, with all fourteen teams that did not qualify for the playoffs eligible to win the picks.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] However, as the worst team is guaranteed one of the first three picks, tanking is still contemplated when the draft field is deep.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In the current scheduling formula which has been in place since 2002 and slightly amended in 2021, only three games in a team's schedule are dependent on a team's placement the previous season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The remaining eight non-division games are the same for all teams in a division.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In addition to the match fixing that is committed by players, coaches and/or team officials, it is not unheard of to have results manipulated by corrupt referees.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Since 2004, separate scandals have erupted in prominent sports leagues in Portugal, Germany (Bundesliga scandal), Brazil (Brazilian football match-fixing scandal) and the United States (see Tim Donaghy scandal), all of which concerned referees who fixed matches for gamblers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Many sports writers have speculated that in leagues with high player salaries, it is far more likely for a referee to become corrupt since their pay in such competitions is usually much less than that of the players.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] On December 2, 1896, former Old West lawman Wyatt Earp refereed the Fitzsimmons vs.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Sharkey boxing match, promoted as the Heavyweight Championship of the World.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Earp was chosen as referee by the National Athletic Association the afternoon of the match after both managers refused to agree on a choice.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In the eighth round of a fight dominated by Fitzsimmons, Sharkey suddenly went down, clutching his groin, yelling foul.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Referee Earp conferred with both corners for a few seconds before he disqualified Fitzsimmons for a foul that virtually no one saw.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Fitzsimmons went to court to attempt to stop Sharkey from taking the purse, but failed when the court ruled that the match was illegal and it had no jurisdiction.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Brookes Lee was arrested in Portland, Oregon.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] He had been accused of treating Sharkey to make it appear that he had been fouled by Fitzsimmons.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Lee said, "I fixed Sharkey up to look as if he had been fouled.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Well, that is something I do not care to reveal, but I will assert that it was done—that is enough.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] There is no doubt that Fitzsimmons was entitled to the decision and did not foul Sharkey.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Match fixing does not necessarily involve deliberately losing a match.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In response, the Football League expanded the divisions to 18 teams that year, thus permitting the intended victims of the fix (Newcastle United and Blackburn Rovers) to remain in the First Division.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The "test match" system was abandoned and replaced with automatic relegation.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A more recent example occurred in the 1982 FIFA World Cup, West Germany played Austria in the last match of group B.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A West German victory by 1 or 2 goals would result in both teams advancing; any less and Germany was out; any more and Austria was out (and replaced by Algeria, who had just beaten Chile).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] West Germany attacked hard and scored after 10 minutes.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Afterwards, the players then proceeded to just kick the ball around aimlessly for the remainder of the match.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Algerian supporters were so angered that they waved banknotes at the players, while a German fan burned his German flag in disgust.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] By the second half, the ARD commentator Eberhard Stanjek refused any further comment on the game, while the Austrian television commentator Robert Seeger advised viewers to switch off their sets.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As a result, FIFA changed its tournament scheduling for subsequent World Cups so that the final pair of matches in each group are played simultaneously.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Another example took place on the next-to-last weekend of the 1992–93 Serie A season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Milan entered their match needing only a point to secure the title ahead of crosstown rivals Inter, while Brescia believed a point would be enough for them to avoid relegation.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The 1–1 draw gave Milan their title, but in the end did not help Brescia; other results went against them and they suffered the drop.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In knockout competitions where the rules require drawn matches to be replayed, teams have sometimes been accused of intentionally playing one or more draws so as to ensure replays.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In this case, the motive is usually financial since the ensuing replay(s) would typically be expected to generate additional revenue for the participating teams.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] One notorious example of this particular type of alleged fix was the 1909 Scottish Cup Final, which sparked a riot after being played twice to a draw.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A team may deliberately lose a match, giving a victory to the opposing team that damages a third-party rival.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] An example of this occurred in Sevilla, Spain, during the 1999–2000 La Liga.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Sevilla FC were in last place and were already officially relegated.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In their thirty-fifth match of the season (out of 38), Sevilla faced Real Oviedo of Asturias, which was itself fighting to avoid relegation.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] An Oviedo victory would put Sevilla's fierce cross-town rival, Real Betis, in the relegation zone.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Sevilla performed poorly, while their fans showed support for Oviedo and expressed concern for missed scoring chances by the Asturian side.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Oviedo defeated Sevilla 3–2, contributing to the eventual relegation of Betis.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Twelve years later, former Sevilla goalkeeper Frode Olsen admitted the team had lost intentionally in order to relegate Betis.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Similarly, a National Football League (NFL) team has also been accused of throwing its final regular-season game in an attempt to keep a rival out of the playoffs.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In addition to the aforementioned incidents of alleged fixing of drawn matches to ensure replays, mutual fixes have sometimes been alleged in "best of X" knockout series where draws are either not possible or very uncommon.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Early versions of baseball's World Series were a common target of such allegations.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Partly as an effort to avoid this sort of controversy, early World Series sometimes saw all scheduled games played even if the Series winner was already determined.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] That did not prove satisfactory since few fans were willing to pay to watch dead rubber contests.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Among other things, the so-called "Brush Rules" stipulated that the players would only receive a share of ticket revenue from the first four games, thus eliminating any financial incentive for the players to deliberately prolong the World Series.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] On several occasions, creative use of tie-breaking rules have allegedly led teams to play less than their best.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] An example occurred in the 2004 European Football Championship.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Unlike FIFA, UEFA takes the result of the game between the two tied teams (or in a three-way tie, the overall records of the games played with the teams in question only) into consideration before overall goal difference when ranking teams level on points.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A situation arose in Group C where Sweden and Denmark played to a 2–2 draw, which was a sufficiently high scoreline to eliminate Italy (which had lower-scoring draws with the Swedes and Danes) regardless of Italy's result with already-eliminated Bulgaria.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The same situation happened to Italy in 2012, leading to many pre-game complaints from Italy, who many commentators suggested were right to be concerned because of their own extensive experience in this area.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] However, Spain-Croatia ended in a 1–0 win for Spain, and the Italians went through.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The FIFA tie-breaker, or any goal-differential scheme, can cause problems, too.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] There have been incidents (especially in basketball) where players on a favored team have won the game but deliberately ensured the quoted point spread was not covered (see point shaving).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Conversely, there are cases where a team not only lost (which might be honest) but lost by some large amount, perhaps to ensure a point spread was covered, or to grant some non-gambling related favor to the victor.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Perhaps the most famous alleged example was the match between Argentina and Peru in the 1978 FIFA World Cup.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Argentina needed a four-goal victory over Peru in order to advance over Brazil, a large margin at this level of competition, yet Argentina won 6–0.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Much was made over possible political collusion, that the Peruvian goalkeeper was born in Argentina, and that Peru was dependent on Argentinian grain shipments, but nothing was ever proven.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Tie-breaking rules played the central role in one of cricket's more notorious matches.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In a 1979 match in England's now-defunct Benson & Hedges Cup, a one-day league, Worcestershire hosted Somerset in the final group match for both sides.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Going into that match, Somerset led their group with three wins from three matches, but would end in a three-way tie for the top spot if they lost to Worcestershire and Glamorgan defeated the then-winless Minor Counties South.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In that event, the tie-breaker would be bowling strike rate.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Somerset players calculated that a large enough loss could see them miss the quarter-finals.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Accordingly, Somerset captain Brian Rose determined that if Somerset batted first and declared their innings closed after one over, they would protect their strike rate advantage, assuring advancement to the quarter-finals.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] When Somerset won the toss, Rose implemented the plan, batting in the first partnership and declaring at the close of the first over after Somerset scored only one run on a no-ball.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Worcestershire won during their second over.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Rose's strategy, although not against the letter of the rules, was condemned by media and cricket officials, and the Test and County Cricket Board (predecessor to the current England and Wales Cricket Board) voted to expel Somerset from that season's competition.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A player can concede with the understanding that the opponent will share the prize equally with him or her.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Depending on the game, this can lead to disqualification.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] On occasion, teams tank games as a protest against actions in earlier games.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The most lopsided professional football match in history, AS Adema 149–0 SO l'Emyrne, was a result of SO l'Emyrne intentionally losing the game in protest against the referee's action in a previous game.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Sometimes, match fixing may simply be motivated by ownership having controlling interests in two or more teams.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] In such circumstances, there is often incentive for the common owners' poorer team to deliberately lose to a championship contender, or at least to make roster and/or coaching decisions that increase the contenders' chances of winning.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Such collusion is often not limited to individual games, rather, owners may deliberately try to transfer all of their best players to the more lucrative team.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] A particularly notorious example occurred in the 1899 Major League Baseball season when the owners of the Cleveland Spiders bought a more profitable team, the St.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Louis Perfectos, and brazenly traded Cleveland's best players to St.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The Spiders finished the season 20–134 (by far the worst record in MLB history) and were contracted after the season.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Modern major sports leagues usually prohibit such ownership arrangements.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Where it is necessary or desirable for a single ownership group to control two teams, salary caps often limit the ability of owners to stack one roster at the expense of another.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Typically, to forestall so much as any perception of impropriety, such teams will be prohibited from trading directly with each other and any head-to-head match(es) will usually be scheduled early in the season to ensure there are no obvious championship and/or playoff implications.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] An example of this arrangement occurred in the early 21st century in the Canadian Football League; between 2010 and 2015, the BC Lions and the Toronto Argonauts were owned by the same person.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Bookmakers in the early 21st century accept bets on a far wider range of sports-related propositions than ever before.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Thus, a gambling-motivated fix might not necessarily involve any direct attempt to influence the outright result, especially in team sports in which such a fix would require the co-operation (and prerequisitely the knowledge) of many people and/or perhaps would be more likely to arouse suspicion.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Fixing the result of a more-particular proposition might be seen as less likely to be noticed.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Likewise, a tennis pro was paid to make sure she lost her first service game.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] She was free to play normally for the rest of the match.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Similarly, in 2010, Pakistani cricket players were accused of committing specific no-ball penalties for the benefit of gamblers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The scandal centred on three Pakistani players accepting bribes from a bookmaker, Mazhar Majeed, during the Lord's test match against England.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Following investigations by the News of the World and Scotland Yard, on 1 November 2011, Majeed, Pakistan's captain, Salman Butt, Mohammad Asif and Mohammad Amir were found guilty of conspiracy to cheat at gambling and to accept corrupt payments.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] As a result, all three of the players were banned by the International Cricket Council (ICC): Butt for ten years, Asif for seven and Amir for five.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] On 3 November 2011, jail terms were handed down of 30 months for Butt, one year for Asif, six months for Amir and two years eight months for Majeed.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Whenever any serious motivation for teams to manipulate results becomes apparent to the general public, there can be a corresponding effect on betting markets as honest gamblers speculate in good faith as to the chance such a fix might be attempted.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Some bettors might choose to avoid wagering on such a fixture while others will be motivated to wager on it, or alter the bet they would otherwise place.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] Such actions will invariably affect odds and point spreads even if there is no contact whatsoever between teams and the relevant gambling interests.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p01] The rise of betting exchanges has allowed such speculation to play out in real time.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Evidence of match fixing has been found throughout recorded history, and the history of match fixing is closely related to the history of illegal gambling.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The ancient Olympic Games were almost constantly dealing with allegations of athletes accepting bribes to lose a competition and city-states which often tried to manipulate the outcome with large amounts of money.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] These activities went on despite the oath each athlete took to protect the integrity of the events and the severe punishment sometimes inflicted on those who were caught.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Chariot racing was also dogged by race fixing throughout its history.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] By the end of the 19th century, gambling was illegal in most jurisdictions, but that did not stop its widespread practice.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Boxing soon became rife with fighters "taking a dive", likely due to boxing being a sport involving individual competitors, which makes its matches much easier to fix without getting caught.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Baseball also became plagued by match fixing despite efforts by the National League to stop gambling at its games.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Matters finally came to a head in 1919 when eight members of the Chicago White Sox threw the World Series.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In an effort to restore confidence, Major League Baseball established the office of the Commissioner of Baseball, and one of Kenesaw Mountain Landis's first acts was to ban all involved players for life.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] MLB Rule 21 prohibits players from participating in any form of betting on baseball games, and a lifetime ban for betting on a player's own games.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] A poster with Rule 21 must be posted on all professional baseball clubhouses.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In the 1990s, match fixing in Asia was especially common.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In Malaysia, authorities suggested that 70% of football matches were being manipulated, and corruption scandals in China resulted in gamblers choosing to bet on overseas matches.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Economists using statistical analysis have shown very strong evidence of bout fixing in sumo wrestling.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Most of the motive for match fixing is helping each other's ranking to keep their salary higher, according to Keisuke Itai.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The sumo association appears to make a distinction between *yaocho* (the payment of money to secure a result) and *koi-ni-yatta mukiryoku zumo* (the deliberate performance of underpowered sumo in which an opponent simply lays a match down without exchange of money).
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Some of the most notorious instances of match fixing have been observed in international cricket.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In 2000 the Delhi police intercepted a conversation between a blacklisted bookie and the South African cricket captain Hansie Cronje in which they learnt that Cronje accepted money to throw matches.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] A court of inquiry was set up and Cronje admitted to throwing matches.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] He was immediately banned from all cricket.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] He also named Saleem Malik (Pakistan), Mohammed Azharuddin and Ajay Jadeja (India) as fellow match fixers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Although Cronje was a kingpin of betting, following untimely death in 2002 most of his fixing partners escaped law enforcement agencies.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Earlier in 1998, Australian players Mark Waugh and Shane Warne were fined for revealing information about the 'weather' to a bookmaker.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The fourth Test of Pakistan's summer 2010 cricket tour of England contained several incidents of spot fixing, involving members of Pakistan team deliberately bowling no-balls at specific points to facilitate betting through bookmakers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Following investigation, three Pakistani players were banned from cricket and sentenced to prison terms.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Similarly, in Indian Premier League in 2013, S.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Sreesanth and two other players were banned by the Board of Control for Cricket in India for alleged match fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Sreesanth's ban was briefly lifted, but the Kerala High Court upheld the ban in 2017.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In July 2017, ex-Sri Lanka cricket captain Arjuna Ranatunga alleged that the 2011 Cricket World Cup Final match between India and Sri Lanka had been fixed.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The investigation was dropped by Sri Lankan authorities and the International Cricket Council in 2020 due to a lack of evidence.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In July 2022, it was reported that local authorities had shut down an operation in Gujarat, India, that had been running a fictitious, kayfabe version of the Indian Premier League in an attempt to scam Russian sports betters.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The matches took place on a field with floodlights, with players dressed in replica jerseys of real IPL teams; based on bets received on a Telegram channel, umpires instructed the players and "referees" to perform specific plays and calls.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Broadcasts of the "matches" were streamed on YouTube, and utilized artificial crowd noise, a sound-alike of cricket commentator Harsha Bhogle, and camera angles that never showed clear shots of the pitch, players, or deliveries.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The participating players were paid 400 rupees per-game, and the operation was estimated to have scammed punters out of 300,000 rupees before it was shut down by police.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The actual 2022 Indian Premier League had already concluded at the end of May.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The issue of match fixing in association football has been described in 2013 by Chris Eaton, the former Head of Security of FIFA (the sport's world governing body), as a "crisis", while UEFA's president Michel Platini has said that if it continues, "football is dead".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Zhang Jilong, president of the Asian Football Confederation, has stated that it is a "pandemic".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The issue also affects a number of other sports across the world.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In May 2011, world governing body FIFA announced an anti-match fixing plan, and in September 2012 FIFA President Sepp Blatter warned that match-fixing endangered "the integrity of the game".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In September 2014, the Council of Europe also announced they would tackle the problem.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] A number of clubs in countries across the world have been subject to match fixing, including Australia, China, and Spain.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The South African national team has also been investigated.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In the 18 months prior to February 2013, Europol investigated 680 matches in 30 countries.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In November 2013, 11 men were charged in Estonia with fixing 17 matches.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The problem is often attributed to criminal gangs based in Asia, who generate "hundreds of billions of euros per year".
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Players who have publicly rejected bribes have been praised, such as in a case in Belize.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Sportradar Integrity Services identified 721 suspicious soccer matches in 72 countries in 2024 and 881 matches in 83 countries in 2023.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Suspicious activity mostly occurred in live betting and primarily involved suspected manipulations of the winning goal margin or total goals in a march.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In professional wrestling, most matches have predetermined results; however, as it is an open secret that professional wrestling is staged, it is not considered match fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Up until the 1920s, professional wrestling was considered a legitimate sport.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] This did not endure as professional wrestling became identified with modern theatrics or *admitted fakery*, moving away from actual competition.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The "worked", known as "kayfabe" nature of wrestling led critics to deem it an illegitimate sport, particularly in comparison to boxing, amateur wrestling, and, more recently, mixed martial arts.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Many individuals began to doubt the legitimacy of wrestling after the retirement of Frank Gotch in 1913.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] As wrestling's popularity was diving around the same time that Major League Baseball had its own legitimacy issues, wrestling started to take on a more worked approach while still appearing as a legitimate sport, beginning with the Gold Dust Trio of the 1920s.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Even after the formation of the National Wrestling Alliance in 1948, wrestling continued to have legitimacy issues.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The move was seen as more of a relief to those who had questioned wrestling's legitimacy, since at least one major company (in this case, the WWF) was now publicly willing to admit that wrestling was staged; however, the move did anger many wrestling purists.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Due to the lingering legitimacy issues that surrounded wrestling from the 1910s until the 1980s, gambling was generally not allowed on wrestling matches while it was still considered a legitimate sport.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Despite wrestling having openly acknowledged that the results are predetermined for years, since the late 2000s gambling has increased on wrestling events, though the maximum bets are kept low due to the matches being predetermined.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In the 1950s, the producers of several televised quiz shows in the United States were found to have engaged in match fixing, as part of an effort to boost viewer interest and ratings.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Geritol, the sponsor of the new quiz show *Twenty-One*, showed concerns over the poor performance of its early contestants—which they felt were causing the show to trail behind its main competitor, *The $64,000 Question*.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] At the time, the majority of television programs were effectively controlled by their single sponsors, with broadcasters only providing studios and airtime.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Geritol demanded that Barry & Enright Productions make changes to the show, which included the outright choreography of contestants around predetermined outcomes.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The most infamous example of this strategy came when champion Herbert Stempel was to be replaced by Charles Van Doren—a Columbia University English teacher whom the producers felt would be more popular with viewers.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] On *Twenty-One*, winners of matches received $500 for every point within their margin of victory, but this pot increased by $500 after every tie game.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] To build anticipation for the episode where Van Doren would defeat Stempel, the first episode of their match was played to three tie games; this meant that the next game would be played for $2,000 per-point.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] After one more tie game, Stempel threw the match to Van Doren by answering specific questions incorrectly.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Among them, he incorrectly guessed that *On the Waterfront* was the winner of the Best Picture award at the 28th Academy Awards.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The correct answer was *Marty*, which was also one of Stempel's favorite films.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The cancellation of the competing quiz *Dotto* under similar allegations prompted a U.S. government investigation into both it and *Twenty-One*.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] The scandal prompted the passage of a federal law prohibiting broadcasters from carrying fixed contests resembling any game of chance or intellectual skill.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Notably, one quiz show, *Our Little Genius*, was cancelled before its premiere after accusations that the outcome was being scripted.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Match fixing controversies have also emerged in Esports, including in particular *Counter-Strike: Global Offensive*, *Dota 2*, *League of Legends*, *Overwatch*, *Paladins*, and *StarCraft*.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] South Korean *StarCraft II* player Life was also convicted of having partaken in match fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] By monitoring the pre-match betting markets it is sometimes possible to detect planned match fixing.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] It is also possible to detect on-going match manipulation by looking at the in-game betting markets.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Several federations have employed services that provide such systems for detecting match manipulation.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] Prior to the 2016 MLB season, Major League Baseball (MLB) hired Genius Sports, a sports technology company specialising in integrity, to monitor the betting patterns on all of their games.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In addition, Interpol monitors and publishes major developments in match-fixing and corruption in sports around the world.
[src:match-fixing/match-fixing-p02] In addition, several federations run integrity tours where players and officials participate in educational workshops on how match fixing work and how they are prevented.
